(Cite as: 1 A.K.Marsh. 535,  8 Ky. 535 (Ky.),  1819 WL 1071 (Ky.)) Court of Appeals of Kentucky. Alvin Mountjoy v. Tyree Oldham. May 31, 1819. *1 ON A WRIT OF ERROR TO REVERSE AN ORDER OF THE PENDLETON COUNTY COURT. West Headnotes Eminent Domain 148 k 198(1) 148 Eminent Domain 148III Proceedings to Take Property and Assess Compensation 148k198 Hearing and Determination as to Right to Take 148k198(1) k. In General. Most Cited Cases An inquest on a writ of ad quod damnum, on a mill seat, is fatally defective if it omits to state whether or not the health of the neighbors will be affected. JUDGE OWSLEY DELIVERED THE OPINION OF THE COURT: We are of opinion that the inquisition taken in this cause, is fatally defective, in not stating whether or not the health of the neighbors, by the stagnation of the waters, will be annoyed; and that the county court, upon the return of the inquisition, consequently erred in giving leave to build the mill. An inquest on a writ of ad quod damnum on a mill seat, is fatally defective if it omits to state whether or not the health of the neighbors will be annoyed. Vide post--Majors v. Taylor, acc. The order must therefore be reversed with cost, the cause remanded, and further proceedings had, not inconsistent with this opinion. Talbot for plaintiff, Haggin for defendant. Ky.App. 1819. Mountjoy v. Oldham 1 A.K.Marsh. 535, 8 Ky. 535, 1819 WL 1071 (Ky.) END OF DOCUMENT
